SUDDEN DECLINE, MANGO - PAKISTAN: (SINDH)
*****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 7 Apr 2021
Source: The Express Tribune [edited]
https://tribune.com.pk/story/2293590/contagious-crop-disease-plagues-sindhs-mango-fields


Mangoes are under threat in Sindh by the fast-spreading mango death syndrome. "It causes the leaves and flowers to suddenly turn brown, wither, wilt and drop to the ground," explains a [mango grower]. It is for the 1st time that his orchard [of] 60 acres has been infected to such a vast extent. "Experts call it the sudden death disease. There is no other option but to cut the infected twigs and branches," he laments. "Growers also need to be more careful as the mango death syndrome can easily spread from one farm or orchard to the other," he warned.

According to growers, the syndrome has affected 20 to 30 percent of mango orchards in Sindh [including] areas in lower Sindh where the disease has caused panic among the growers. A mango grower [on] 100 acres [says],
"Around 20 to 25 percent of my crop has been damaged." According to him, Sindh's growers face a similar situation every year, but the problem is more serious this year [2021]. "And no one has bothered to conduct research and come up with a remedy," he laments. [He] connects it to the rise in the temperature during February.

[A local commercial] Fruit Farm also say that mango orchards being plagued by diseases was nothing new, but the damage has been caused to a greater extent this [2021] year. However, research is underway and [they] are hopeful that a solution to the problem would soon be found. Elaborating on the types of diseases, the mango death syndrome consists of various decaying diseases.

[Byline: Hafeez Tunio]

