Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Mango (_Mangifera indica_) is one of the most important fruits worldwide. The term 'mango sudden decline syndrome' (MSDS) is used to describe one or a series of diseases and disease symptoms, including blight, canker, gummosis, twig blight, tip dieback and vascular staining. MSDS (or quick decline, sudden wilt) is of great economic importance since the trees die within a very short time. Countries currently severely affected by MSDS include Pakistan, Oman and Brazil.

Several fungi, including _Lasiodiplodia theobromae_ and _Ceratocystis_ species, have been reported to be associated with MSDS in different areas. It has been suggested that nutrient deficiencies and environmental stress factors may increase the susceptibility of mango trees to sudden decline. Bark beetles (_Hypocryphalus mangiferae_) were shown to carry _C. fimbriata_ and _L. theobromae_ and are also thought to be responsible for transmitting some of the other fungal species.

Some fungicides were found to be helpful if applied quickly enough, but genetic resistance is considered the best means of disease management. Control programmes established in Oman (ProMED-mail post 20091214.4240) use exotic rootstocks from various countries with degrees of resistance to sudden decline which are grafted with scions of local varieties. It is hoped that this will produce trees suitable to local conditions but showing resistance to the pathogens. Screening of indigenous germplasm will be an important means for finding possible genetic resistance in mango varieties for breeding and/or use as rootstocks.

